There's not a great way to do this on the field itself, but you could override the `to_value` method in your custom serializer like this (code not tested but idea should work):

```py
class MySerializer(serpy.Serializer):
    def set_defaults(self, v):
        for name, _, _, _, _, _ in self._compiled_fields:
            v.setdefault(name)
        return v

    def to_value(self, instance):
        v = super(MySerializer, self).to_value(instance)
        if self.many:
            return map(self.set_defaults, v)
        return self.set_defaults(v)
```

Let me know if that will solve your issue.

If you already have the select2 set up using the filterFormatter, then use the initialization and filter end event to update the external select2 data.

```js
$(function(){

	$('.external-select2').select2({
		/* whatever options */
	});

	// zero-based index of select2 column
	var select2Column = 2,
		// only get available (filter-onlyAvail) rows
		onlyAvail = false;

	$('table')
		.tablesorter({
			/* whatever options */
		})
		.on('tablesorter-initialized filterEnd', function(){
			var	data = [],
			arry = $.tablesorter.filter.getOptionSource( this, select2Column, onlyAvail) || [];
			// build select2 data option
			$.each(arry, function(i,v){
				data.push({id: v, text: v});
			});
			// update select2 with new data
			$('.external-select2').select2('data', data, true);
		});

});
```

