Thanks @Fedalto, I tried to dive in. Ultimately all `is_mapped_class(model)` does is call [`def manager_of_class(cls)`](https://github.com/zzzeek/sqlalchemy/blob/8f7766cc61479f3c9220c640230eeecd3d49ccc8/lib/sqlalchemy/orm/base.py#L208), in the `orm/base.py` module, using your defined model. It's a tiny function with does the following:

    def manager_of_class(cls):
        return cls.__dict__.get(DEFAULT_MANAGER_ATTR, None)

... where `DEFAULT_MANAGER_ATTR = '_sa_class_manager'`.

In essence it requires that you're model has a field '_sa_class_manager' if not it returns `None` then propagates the error up.

I don't think a class manager is set when you use reflection, i.e., through inheriting from `Base=automap_base()` when defining your models. I don't think there is anything wrong with @rvandyk's models, it's just that `graphene_sqlalchemy` assumes all SqlAlchemy models are structured the same, and it seems they aren't.

